WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.020
Music

00:05.020 --> 00:10.020
Music

00:10.020 --> 00:15.020
Music

00:15.020 --> 00:20.020
Music

00:20.020 --> 00:25.020
Music

00:25.020 --> 00:44.900
So our first groundwork exercise is going to be to move the shoulder over from the ground.

00:44.900 --> 00:54.780
So some key points are that the horse does not step forward into your space.

00:54.780 --> 01:00.540
Imagine you have a little bubble around yourself and they can't step forward.

01:00.540 --> 01:07.300
So you see me there correcting him every time he tries to push his nose, his body, his energy

01:07.300 --> 01:11.100
into my space.

01:11.100 --> 01:14.400
So it's important also to know what type of horse you're dealing with.

01:14.400 --> 01:18.880
This is a semi-reactive three-year-old gelding.

01:18.880 --> 01:21.240
So he likes to play with things.

01:21.240 --> 01:23.120
He likes rewards.

01:23.120 --> 01:28.440
So find out what your horse likes and give them that as a reward.

01:28.440 --> 01:34.680
So if they like to have a little walk around so that they can go forward from this exercise,

01:34.680 --> 01:36.220
that's a great reward.

01:36.220 --> 01:43.480
If they want to be pet on the forehead like this horse, that's a great reward.

01:43.480 --> 01:47.120
If they want a treat, carry treats in your pocket.

01:47.120 --> 01:51.000
Just be mindful that they're not abusing any of their rewards.

01:51.000 --> 01:58.200
Now the purpose of this exercise is for them to not step forward into your bubble, your

01:58.200 --> 01:59.200
energy bubble.

01:59.200 --> 02:06.000
So you see me not moving my feet, he cannot walk on top of me at all.

02:06.000 --> 02:09.240
And when he does it well, then he gets a reward.

02:09.240 --> 02:17.040
The other thing is normally we would like the foot to step behind the other forefoot.

02:17.040 --> 02:22.880
But in this case, when you're brand new to this exercise, it doesn't matter if it steps

02:22.880 --> 02:29.880
forward or behind, except a sideward step no matter how it looks.

02:29.880 --> 02:31.400
Just like that, exactly.

02:31.400 --> 02:33.600
And then forward pet.

02:33.600 --> 02:38.740
Now you see me squatting there, that is to encourage the horse's head to come down.

02:38.740 --> 02:43.580
Something that horses have a hard time with is putting their head down without walking

02:43.580 --> 02:45.060
forward.

02:45.060 --> 02:50.380
So make sure you teach them that in some way before you start this exercise.

02:50.380 --> 02:51.380
Okay?

02:51.380 --> 02:58.300
And you see me constantly correcting him from stepping into me, and that's very important.

02:58.300 --> 03:02.720
Some other horses we're going to want to step away from you in which you have to draw them

03:02.720 --> 03:06.300
in with the pet or in with the rein.

03:06.300 --> 03:10.940
You can do this without a saddle on, just a halter.

03:10.940 --> 03:15.300
I like using a bridle so I have both sides of the bit.

03:15.300 --> 03:20.340
And later on they can be in a halter or a rope halter to make sure that they understand

03:20.340 --> 03:22.340
the exercise.

03:22.340 --> 03:31.020
Good, as simple as that, just moving the shoulder over one step at a time.

03:31.020 --> 03:36.020
You notice immediately when he starts to move, then I snap the whip back and release him

03:36.020 --> 03:40.900
completely from the exercise.

03:40.900 --> 03:45.580
And spend time in reward.

03:45.580 --> 03:51.700
If they really enjoy having a walk or if they really enjoy having a pet, spend time there.

03:51.700 --> 03:57.440
Talk to them, give them what they need to feel like they've done a good job, especially

03:57.440 --> 04:05.220
with these young horses or horses just that are wanting to please, they need to know that

04:05.420 --> 04:10.820
they've done the exercise correctly.

04:10.820 --> 04:17.280
It's important for you as students to see the entire process of how we get to the point

04:17.280 --> 04:21.360
of him actually accomplishing the task with consistency.

04:21.360 --> 04:26.380
So that's why I've shown you all these videos.

04:26.380 --> 04:33.860
So now by the end of the little session here, he's not only more responsible for not running

04:33.860 --> 04:39.760
over top of me, so I'm being a little more strict about him not running on top of me,

04:39.760 --> 04:44.020
but also he is much more accustomed to the exercise.

04:44.020 --> 04:48.060
He has a good understanding of what's expected of him.

04:48.060 --> 04:50.260
And there you go, perfect.

04:50.260 --> 04:51.600
Good boy.

04:51.600 --> 04:57.040
So the squatting down is really working for this horse to bring his head down, which is

04:57.040 --> 05:03.020
important for his spine to come into a neutral position and relax.

05:03.020 --> 05:06.600
And also a very obvious reward, perfect.

05:06.600 --> 05:09.400
One step is all you need.

05:09.400 --> 05:11.160
There you have it, your first exercise.

